                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Merge Intervals is the canonical technique for problems where ranges, time windows, or segments must be collapsed, queried, or scheduled. The core invariant is simple: sort intervals by start time, then greedily merge any new interval that overlaps with the running "current" interval by extending its end to max(current.end, next.end). It appears in nearly every FAANG interview loop because it models real-world problems (calendar scheduling, CPU task assignment, memory allocation, genomic range queries) and because the technique sits at a productive intersection of sorting, greedy reasoning, and sweep-line thinking. Extensions — like inserting into a pre-sorted list, partitioning into groups, or counting overlapping depth — test the engineer's ability to reason about the invariant rather than just recite the algorithm.</div>
                    <div class="core-box"><strong>Core Invariant:</strong> Sort by start. Maintain a "current" interval. For each next interval: if next.start ≤ current.end, merge by setting current.end = max(current.end, next.end); otherwise, push current to result and start a new current = next. <strong>Key variants:</strong> sort-by-end for removal/coverage; two-pointer for intersection; sweep line with +1/−1 for depth.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="pill-grid">
                        <span class="pill">Merge all overlapping intervals</span>
