                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statements</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>🔧 #12 — Count Interval Depth at Query Points:</strong> Given N intervals [start_i, end_i] and Q query points, return for each query point p the number of intervals containing p. Constraints: 1 ≤ N, Q ≤ 10⁵, 0 ≤ start_i ≤ end_i ≤ 10⁹, 0 ≤ p ≤ 10⁹. Example: intervals [[1,5],[2,8],[4,7]]; query 3 → 2; query 6 → 2; query 9 → 0. Key Insight: Coordinate-compress all starts, ends+1, and query points. Build a difference array (+1 at start, -1 at end+1). Sort and take prefix sums. Answer each query by binary searching the compressed coordinate array. This is the offline sweep-line extension of merge intervals.</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>🔧 #30 — Weighted Interval Scheduling:</strong> Given N intervals with start, end, and weight, select a maximum-weight subset of non-overlapping intervals. Constraints: 1 ≤ N ≤ 10⁵, 0 ≤ start_i &lt; end_i ≤ 10⁹, 1 ≤ weight_i ≤ 10⁴. Example: [[1,3,5],[2,5,6],[4,6,5],[6,8,4]] → 10 ([1,3] weight 5 + [4,6] weight 5). Key Insight: Sort by end. dp[i] = max weight using intervals 1..i where interval i is included. Binary search for last j where end[j] ≤ start[i]. dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], weight[i] + dp[j]). Greedy merge cannot optimise weights.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Trigger Phrase</th><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>When It BREAKS</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Merge/combine all overlapping ranges..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Sort by start; linear sweep; merge when current.end ≥ next.start</td><td class="trigger-breaks">Never breaks for plain merge</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Insert a new interval into a sorted list..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Three-phase O(n) insertion: skip left, merge overlapping, copy right</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If list is unsorted → must sort first (O(n log n))</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Minimum rooms / workers / resources needed simultaneously..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Maximum overlap depth; sort start/end events, two-pointer sweep</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If queries are online with updates → need segment tree</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Remove fewest intervals so none overlap..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Sort by end (not start); greedy keep earliest-ending intervals</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If intervals have weights → requires DP, not greedy</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Cover a full range [0, N] using minimum intervals..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Greedy coverage: among intervals starting ≤ current_reach, extend to farthest end</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If gaps are not allowed → stricter coverage variant</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Find free / available time slots..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Merge all busy intervals; gaps = free time</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If multiple calendars → merge each calendar first, then intersect gaps</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"How many intervals contain point p / events active at time t..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Sweep line: +1 at start, −1 at end+1; prefix sum gives depth</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If many queries → offline sweep with coordinate compression</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Calendar conflicts / booking system / prevent double-booking..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Maintain sorted interval set (TreeMap); check overlap with floor/ceiling</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If triple-booking or k-booking → maintain multiple overlap lists or delta map</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"Two sorted interval lists — find all overlapping pairs..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Two-pointer intersection: advance pointer with smaller end</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If lists are unsorted → sort first</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="trigger-phrase">"N buildings — output the silhouette / skyline..."</td><td class="trigger-variant">Sweep line + max-heap or TreeMap on heights</td><td class="trigger-breaks">If buildings are static → can pre-process; if dynamic → segment tree</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Weighted intervals (maximise total value)</strong> — Greedy merge cannot optimise weights; requires DP with binary search for last non-overlapping interval. Standard merge gives wrong answers for weighted variants.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Non-contiguous selection (subsequence, not subarray)</strong> — If the problem allows skipping intervals freely with no coverage requirement, it's a DP/knapsack problem, not interval merging.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Interval DP (burst balloons, stone merge)</strong> — Problems where optimal solution depends on ORDER of merging require O(n³) interval DP, not O(n log n) sweep.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Online queries with modifications AND range queries</strong> — Static merge/sort cannot answer queries after insertions; need a segment tree or interval tree.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Touching-but-not-overlapping boundary ambiguity</strong> — Whether [1,3] and [3,5] are "overlapping" depends on open/closed interval semantics. Verify the problem's definition before using ≥ vs >.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Circular intervals</strong> — Intervals that wrap around a modular boundary (e.g., [350°, 30°] in angles) require special handling: split into two linear intervals or rotate the domain.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 — Solve (in order):</strong> #1 → #2 → #3 → #4 → #5 → #6 → #13 → #15 → #17 → #22 → #23 → #8 → #20 → #25 → #24 → #28 → #31<br>
                        Problems 1–3 establish the three pillars: merge, insert, intersect. Problems 4–5 teach the sort-by-end greedy (fundamentally different from sort-by-start merge). Problem 6 trains maximum-depth sweep — the most commonly asked interval variant at Google. Problem 13 introduces containment (not just overlap). Problems 15 + 28 teach the coverage greedy — same algorithm, two different disguises. Problems 20 → 22 → 23 build the online TreeMap insertion skill progressively (easy → hard). Problem 24 (Skyline) is the peak implementation challenge — tackle last in Phase 1.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 — Drill:</strong> Before coding, classify each problem as one of these 5 actions: merge / insert / depth / remove / cover. Separately drill sort-by-start vs. sort-by-end; know which variant to use for which action. Time yourself: #1, #2, #3 should be solvable in ≤ 10 minutes each after first pass; #4, #5, #6 in ≤ 15 minutes.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 — Validate:</strong> LeetCode contest archive — filter "interval" tag in contest problems; solve 3 unseen problems under 25-minute time limit. Codeforces — problems tagged [greedy][sortings] rated 1500–1800 — many are interval scheduling/coverage in disguise. USACO Silver — "Rental Service", "Paired Up" — use sweep-line + greedy on sorted events.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">80% Coverage Set</div>
                    <div class="coverage-box"><strong>Minimum 10 problems:</strong> <span class="pill">LC 56</span><span class="pill">LC 57</span><span class="pill">LC 986</span><span class="pill">LC 435</span><span class="pill">LC 253</span><span class="pill">LC 759</span><span class="pill">LC 1024</span><span class="pill">LC 352</span><span class="pill">LC 218</span><span class="pill">LC 312 ⚠️</span></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Sorting by end time when you should sort by start (or vice versa)</strong> — Core merge and insert require sort-by-start; minimum removal and arrow/pierce problems require sort-by-end. Mixing these up silently produces wrong answers on all non-trivial inputs.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Using current.end ≥ next.start for open intervals</strong> — If interval boundaries are exclusive (open), [1,3) and [3,5) do not overlap; the correct condition is current.end > next.start. Always confirm open vs. closed from the problem statement.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Forgetting to take max when extending the merged end</strong> — Writing current.end = next.end instead of current.end = max(current.end, next.end) fails when a shorter interval is fully contained within the current one (e.g., [1,10] followed by [2,4]).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Three-phase insert: adding the merged interval too early</strong> — In LC 57, the merged interval must be finalised (after absorbing all overlapping intervals) before being appended; appending it during the merge loop causes duplicates or premature termination.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Maximum depth with single sorted event list instead of two separate start/end lists</strong> — Using one event list with tie-breaking instead of the cleaner two-pointer approach over separately sorted starts and ends leads to subtle off-by-one errors at coincident start/end times.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Applying greedy merge to a weighted interval problem</strong> — The most conceptually dangerous mistake: greedy merge optimises for coverage or count, never for total weight. If the problem has values/weights attached to intervals, always reach for DP first.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Not handling the "no intervals" or "single interval" edge case</strong> — Many implementations start with result.add(intervals[0]) and crash on empty input. Always guard with if (intervals.length == 0) return new int[0][] before any logic.</div>
                </div></div>
